*Short URL Features/Functionality*
------------------------
* By default short urls will be created using our own standard 'short url domain name' (B)
* Short link URLS will have the following format:
	<linkdomain>/<linksuffix>

	Where:
		<linkdomaian> is either the services default domain used for short links or one defined by a registered organisation for use
		<linksuffix> is a randomly generated alphanumeric code of betweeen 4-8 characters (character lengths limits can be configured by the service developer, or customised by the admin or a registered organisation). 
						In the case of use by a registered user (indidividual user or under an organisation) the user is offered the opportunity to customise the <linksuffix> with no limitations to length. The only limitation being that the <linksuffix> must be unique to the <linkdomain> to be used.
* Configured shortlinks should be able to have categories/tags assigned to them to assist with group/identification for analytics purposes.
* Registered users (individuals or as part of another registered organisation) can customise the shortlink suffix
* Registered organisations can 'link' their own custom short URL domain name, where all links generated by a registered user of that organisation will produce links under their own custom shortened domain name.
	* Registered organisations can also configure their own website root domaian names (google.com). When doing so any 'long link' which they wish to shorten, from one of their predefined domains (including multi-level subdomains) are created under their own customer short domain
		* A Mechanism to verify ownership of any owned root website domains should also be possible.

	Example:
		1) Org 'Google' is a registered user of the service.
		2) An admin of the 'Google' registered organisation registers (and verifies) the following domain names as owned by them:
			* Google.com
			* Google.co.uk
			* Google.co.za
		3) An admin of the 'Google' Registered organisation also owns goog.link and registers this to be used for all their generated short domains.
		4A) A registered user of the service, under the 'Google' registered dorganisation wants to create short links for the following URLs
			* google.com/somespecialsearchurlwillgohere
			* maps.google.com/somelongurltoagooglemapsspecialcontentpage
			* google.co.uk/someukspecificlongurlheretoaukspecificpage?refID=q87db92wdsa
		4B) the following (automated, ie no customised <linksuffix>) shortURLs are generated:
			* goog.link/ahsywwd0
			* goog.link/ox8wh20x
			* goog.link/ao92uz0c

	This also ensures/allows that if a anonymous/regular user were to use this service to shorten a Google link (based on this example) a Goog.link shortlink will always be generated, thus keeping Googles print always at the centre! In such cases, analytics for this shortlink will also be visible to the Google Org user account(s).
* As target redirections can differ/change (see definition further down), redirections should be done as transparent 302 redirections.
* Redirections should be done transparently (header) in all cases, except when a brief page is to be displayed (see further specification below), in which case Javascript redirect (with fallback manual link) is acceptible, for obvious technical reasons.
* It must be possible to define a description for a short link (see column urlDescription in the existing Database Structure). This will be used as the 'label'/button for this link if displayed in a LinksPage. Short Link/<linksuffix> created by unregistered/anonymous user will not have this functionality available to them
* It must be possible to define a validity date range for a created short link. ie link will only work/redirect between 1 Jan 2025-3 Jan 2025. (see columns urlStartDate and urlEndDate in the existing database structure) Short Link/<linksuffix> created by unregistered/anonymous user will not have this functionality available to them
* It must be possible to explicitly disable a short link without defined validity dates. Short Link/<linksuffix> created by unregistered/anonymous user will not have this functionality available to them.

  Deletion of short codes shold never be deleted, but instead deactivated within the database
* It must be possible for a user (individual or as an organisation) to define which ShortURLs/links are displayed on the LinksPage (see column allowLinksPage in the existing Database structure) Short Link/<linksuffix> created by unregistered/anonymous user will not have this functionality available to them
* If (using the Google examples above) a user visits goog.link without proviing a <linksuffix>, the "LinksPage' for this 'Google' Organisation should be shown. Short Link/<linksuffix> created by unregistered/anonymous user will not have this functionality available to them. Possible PREMIUM Paid feature
* It must be possible to configure a short link URL to redirect to the final destination of another pre-exxisting short link URL (see column urlID in the existsing database structure) effectively acts as an alias to the other (see column urlRedirAlias in the existsing database structure).  Short Link/<linksuffix> created by unregistered/anonymous user will not have this functionality available to them.
    If we could merge ethe urlRedirAlis and urlRedirLong into one field, and have the system intelligently detect if its a alias or 'proper' destination redirect, that may also be better.

* It must be possible for the destination URL to be validated (if supported) by the 'redirector' before redirection takes place. (see column urlValidateRedirURL in the existing database structure, were we also can explicitly disable destination URL checking both for supported or unsupported destination URLs)
	* Redirection is only supported in some destination contexts. ie HTTP or HTTPS urls for example. This should only be possible for scenarios where the destination URI is verifiable from within PHP.
	* In this case, a verified URI is one returning a 200 OK. A URL returning other codes (especially 404 NOt Found) would fail.
	* Destination URLs that fail validation should present users with a user friendly error message and (configurably) redirect the user to another page (maybe the users/orgnations main websiet) after a (again, configurable) delay.  Short Link/<linksuffix> created by unregistered/anonymous user will not have the functionality to optionally redirect  a failed <linksuffix> to a alternative URL after a short delay.
* It must be posssible to define comments/notes assigned to short link. (see column urlNotes in the existsing database structure). THis can be used by the user remind them what/why the redirect was configured. This can use useful later for audit purposes. This should allow a long string of text.
* A registered Short link <linksuffix> 'owner' must be able to change the destination of a short link <linksuffix> at any time from within the User/Admin Control Panel. Short Link/<linksuffix> created by unregistered/anonymous user will not have this functionality available to them
* Support for entering a Zoom Meeting Code and (if applicable) should be able to identify the full Zoom Meeting URL and create a shortlink/<linksuffix> to that Zoom Meeting (possibly as a PREMIUM PAID feature, still to be decided if paid or free)
* There should also be support for some special, conditional redirections of short links <linksuffix>. Any combination of the allow should be able to be configured by a registered user (individual or organisation). Some of these features and examples listed below may also be restrictured as a PREMIUM PAID feature.
	* It should be possible to define a short link/<linksuffix> as unsuitable for a specific age (ie minimum age). In such cases, the user MUST first be presented with a method by which they can enter their date of birth (with a message saying access to the content is restricted to certain ages, but do not disclose the age). Preferrably use a date picker to ensure we have consistency with date entry formats. On submisssion of visitor DOB, the script should then determine the visitors age on that date/moment in the background, and if the age meets the minimum defined age, redirect as normal. If not of appropriate age, a user friendly message should be displayed stating that access is not permitted.  Short Link/<linksuffix> created by unregistered/anonymous user will not have this functionality available to them. it may also be a premium PAID feature.
	* It should also be possible to have a particular <linksuffix> assigned to a schedule, where depending on the schedule it will redirect to different destination URLs. Example
		* goog.link/magic short link is created, but it this <linksuffix> (magic) redirects to different destinations depending on when it is used/accessed/visited. This sould also support recurring schedules. See an example below:
			* Redirect to images.google.com/abclink on every wednesday between 01:00-07:45
			* Redirect to maps.google.com/abclink2 every Saturday between 10:00-12:00
			* Redirect to news.google.com/abcnewslink on the first Saturday of the month, between 10:00-12:00
			* redirectc to google.com/holidays every year between (25 Dec - 01 Jan, inclusive)
			* Redirect to Sheets.Google.com/somesheetsurl at any other time
	* It must be possible for a short link (<linksuffix> to have multiple destination URLs based on.
		* Device (eg. Windows Laptop/PC, Mac Laptop/PC, Android Phone, Android Tablet, Apple Phone, Aapple Tablet/iPad etc)

	 	Short Link/<linksuffix> created by unregistered/anonymous user will not have this functionality available to them. This will also be a PREMIUM Paid feature

        An example of what this could do....
            * User on iphone visits goog.link/letsgo, is redirected to google.co.uk/letsgo/iphone
            * User on android phone visits goog.link/letsgo, is redirected to google.co.uk/letsgo/android/phone
            * User on android tablet visits goog.link/letsgo, is redirected to google.co.uk/letsgo/android/tablet
            * User on Mac visits goog.link/letsgo, is redirected to google.co.uk/letsgo/Mac
            etc
	* It must also be possible to whitelist/blacklist locations from being able to access a short link, where the defined locataions are stored in the database by ISO 3166-1 and/or ISO 3166-2 codes (as/where applicable.) Whilst the data is stored in the database using ISO Codes, form a user implementation perspective, this must be searchable using a live search.
		* It must also be possible for a single <linksuffix> to redirect to different destination URLs based on the visitor location
* short link acitivty should be logged to allow the 'owner' of the short link to view detailed analytics data from an analytics dashboard within the User/Admin Control Panel. Analytics data should be detailed, but at least provide the following for each shortlink within their account (individual or organisation):
	* URL
	* IP Address (also flag if access was via a VPN/Proxy)
	* Geographic Locataion accessed from. Granularity will vary depending on if GPS info is available or if IP geolocation is used. to protect visitors though, we will never use street level location info. Supported 'levels' include:
		* suburb (PRemium paid feature)
		* City/Town
		* Province/County
		* State (if applicable)
		* Country
		* Content (with disclaimer as to why such a wide area  used)
	* User Agent, including breaking down the following:
		* Browser and Browser version
		* Device
		* Device Model
		* Device Screen Resolution
		* Device Screen Orientation

		Note, not all device level info will always be obtainable.
	* Referring URL

	  Short Link owners should be able to dynamically list the above by hour, day, week, month, year etc. With diagrams (graphs, pie charts etc) being generated to help visualise the data, and place pins on a map for location related info. It should also be possibe to export this info a Excel or similar spreadsheet.
	* Destination Redirect URL
	* Redirect Success/Failure rates

 

* A Modern Web-based UI should be created for the creation of new short links. Management of existing Short Links should be done via the User Control Panel, or Admin Control Panel which can be accessed by logging on on the main homepage of the main website.

------------------------	
*User Accounts*
------------------------
* A user can register an Organisation. This would create the Organisation and their individual user account under that organisation. As the persson creating the organisation, they will also be made Global Admin of that organisation.
	* Organisation Global Admins can also setup new users within the Organisation with either Admin privileges (admin, but with fewer 'powers' than Global Admin.) or Regular USer access.
	* Organisation Regular Users can only create new short links. Modifying of existing short links will be a defineable permission.
	* Organisation Global Admins will also be the only account able to manage which domain names are assoicated with the organisation, manager all users, manage subscription/payments etc.
	* Global Admins will also be able to setup Single Sign On using corporate providers such as (but not necessarily limited to):
		* Microsoft 365
		* Google Workspace
		* self-hosted wordpress.
		
		Any SSO account MUST also be linked to a local/internal account within the application.
		Support for linking multiple accounts from these corporate account providers (MS365, Google Workspace etc) should also be possible, but can be fully configured what limitations there are by the Organisational Global Admin
	* Organisational Admins can 'invite' other members to create an account. this should send an email with a tokanised link which would create the user within the organisation
* A user can register an individual user account. This creates a local/internal user account within the application, as a "User" type.
	* Local 'application' user accounts will also be used as 'universal' accounts for other apps provided by us, so the account setup should also tae this into consideration.
	* A User can also create an account/link their internal 'local'/universal account to one or more from social media provideers (including linking to multiple accounts from the same social media provider, with a limit of up to 3 per social media provider - though this upper limit should be configurable). Supported providers should be:
		* Microsoft Account
		* apple ID
		* Google Account
		* Meta/Facebook logging
		* Yahoo!
		* Amazon Account

		It should also be possible to link any number of these login providers to a local/internal user account
* 2FA and PassKey should also be supported for extra security (with PassKey offering convenience and security)
* Local accounts will be used first, but we plan on rolling out integration with our SIGNula, our other first-party service, via API integration when it is ready for release. Once ready, provide a mechanism to link local account(s) to SIGNula (either via linking to existing SIGNula accounts or creating new ones)

