	*Web Page Design*
------------------------
* In addition to having pre-supplied templates for the LinksPage page designs, It would also be useful, and user-friendly to have the ability for a user/admin to design their own LinksPage page templates using either a blocks-based WYSIWYG editor (where various 'sections' are represented by blocks than can be added/moved/resized into place) or the ability to upload the template as an HTML file. In both cases (WYSIWYG and html upload), their should be the ability to use 'placeholder text markers' that will be replaced by the relevant data (text or images) when the page is displayed
* The LinksPage should also support displaying manually defined links, that do not originate/come from this link shortening service.
* The LinksPage should also have the ability to 'intelligently' detect the favicon of the destination site, and use that within the listing of the relevant link for further user-friendly identification.
* LinksPage should also have the ability to ask for a visitors Date of Birth for age verification purposes. This should be able to be enabled for any link, but should also have a mechanism for them to be automatically added for some adult only websites (OnlyFans etc). As with shortlinks, the age for these should also be definable for all destination links, apart from those with build in configuration of being identified as for 'adults only'

------------------------
	*Web Page Design*
------------------------
* Web pages should be fully responsive, and accommodate all screen sizes & orientations
* Should also be compliant with all current standards
* Should take accessibilty into WCAG compliant to support users with impairements, including a toggle for colour blind users and screenreader support.
* Fully HTML5 compliant and use the latest and greatest HTML5 features, whilst also "gracefully" falling back for browsers that do not support them.
* Styling of the UI should use modern CSS including CSS 3+ and can make use of modern/advanced switches and even animations.
* Pages should indicate to the user that they're logged in, by showing something in the top-right corner (as is commonly the norm in the industry).
  This should display
	* User avatar (in this priority order: Locally stored Bespoke/User Specified/Defined Avatar/Profile Picture from tblUSers in database > MS365/Google Workspace etc > Gravatar > default/placeholder avatar)
	* Name of user
	* A means to change user profile settings (possible via drop-down menu when clicking on Name and Avatar)
* ALL config (with the exception of database connection credentials) should be stored in the Backend MySQL Database (tblSettings table).
    * Database connection credentials to be stored outside of web accessible web paths in relevant _auth_keys/auth_creds.php, which will stored the info, but if ever tried to be accessed directly would not return/echo any info, but should perhaps redirect to the main website (Go2My.Link)
* Some settings, like MS365/Google Workspace etc credentials should also be able to be stored in a private location on the server as a fallback (perhaps also within the relevant _auth_keys/auth_creds.php file as stated above?).
* It should also be possible for new settings to be added at any time by a Global Admin using the Web UI, to minimise requirement to have to manually update PHP Code too much to take these new settings to account.
* Values for settings marked as 'isSensitive' (as well as fields storing ANY user passwords/keys/certs) should be appropriately cryptographically encrypted/hashed to current industry high security/crypographic standards, also using a strong SALT for increased security, to ensure these are safe/secure - but also allow them to be internally decrypted for use as/when required.
* Whilst PHP will be used, the end user should not see this even in places like webpage/form/processor URLs. Not only is this unprofessional but it could also be a security risk as it exposes to potential attackers that PHP is used. Therefore all URLs should be visible as /something/somepage. This can perhaps be achieved by either a router (managed/stored in SQL database), or by simply ensuring the content is in a a location like /something/somepage/index.php (as in the case of the above example)
* Appropriate user-facing error handling should also be implemented, as well as backend error handling for server-side PHP scripts and log these into the Activity Log for later development and fixing by the development and Global Admin teams.
* Form fields (for ALL apps) should
	* Have dynamic field validation wherever possible
	* Use datepickers to ensure consistent format for entered dates.
	* Use ReCaptcha or CloudFlare Turnstile, provided the relevant API Keys are provided (preferred backend database, but fallback in auth.php). If no API Keys provided dont use these technologies for form submission.
* Web pages should also be designed to support use as a WebApp across all supported platforms and browsers, including but not limited to use as a PWA. This can be used for an initial web app until native apps are developed.

